Simulation and Logistic reference from lab

These analyses use the abalone dataset as well as code that all of the lab groups worked on. To run the following code youll need the abalone dataset as well as the code that produced the datasets/models.

The code isnt in this HTML (because it would look ugly), but it is in the .rmd file named logistic_and_simulations.rmd (should be on compass where you found this HTML file). To follow along with this analysis, just open the .rmd file and run all the code up to line 80. The text that youre reading right now starts at line 82.

Simulating from an lm() fit (with predictions as a pit stop)

There are 6 models in this .rmd file that I selected from models that the groups worked on. Please recall that the best model (based on AIC) was a multiple regression model of the form:

\[rings_i=\beta_0+\beta_1\cdot length_i+\beta_2\cdot diameter_i+\beta_3\cdot height_i+\beta_4\cdot whole_i+\beta_5\cdot mature_i +\epsilon_i\] \[\epsilon_i \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2)\]

formula(model.fit)
## rings ~ length + diameter + height + whole + mature

where rings is discrete; length, diameter, height, and whole are continuous; and mature is categorical.

To simulate observations from this model well need to extract the \(\hat{\beta_i}\) (estimates of the \(\beta\)) as well as \(\hat{\sigma}^2\) (the estimate of the varaince).

Well use the summary() function to access the coefficients of the model fit.

summary(model.fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = rings ~ length + diameter + height + whole + mature, 
##     data = data2)
## 
## Residuals:

## -6.0651 -1.6100 -0.4873  0.8494 16.2995

We can extract the \(\hat{\beta_i}\) by just reading them off the summary or by using the coef() function:

coef(model.fit)
## (Intercept)      length    diameter      height       whole     matureM 
##   2.5515305 -11.5266489  18.3895065  42.3253084  -0.7084529   0.9101479

We can extract the standard error of the residuals (\(\hat{\sigma}\)) using the sigma() function:

sigma(model.fit)
## [1] 2.512925

This is the standard error, not the variance.

Dummy variables

Note that mature is a categorical variable with two levels coded as I=infant, M=mature. To fit this in with linear regression, R (and any other program) will convert factor levels to dummy variables. The dummy variable coding here is simple enough: the reference level (I) is coded as 0, the non-reference level (M) is coded as 1. In this simple case with only 2 levels we only need 1 dummy variable column with 2 levels (0 and 1). In general, we need \(k-1\) dummy variables when we have \(k\) levels of a predictor.

For example, lets say we had the original 3 levels (male, female, infant) and that infants were the reference level. Then wed need 2 dummy variables (2 new columns). If we go in alphabetical order for male and femal, then we should have coding like this:

  • Infant would be coded as: (0, 0)
  • Female would be coded as: (1, 0)
  • Male would be coded as : (0, 1)

Note that the dummy variable coding may be confusing if you have used 0 and 1 as the named factor levels. (Case in point: creating an inverse ROC curve). Dummy variable coding is based on which level is the reference level. The factor level could be 1, or 99, or banana but if you force it to be the reference level then the dummy coding is 0. The mature (factor level =M) has dummy variable equal to 1 in this example (and so imature is coded as 0).

Predictions

The \(\hat{y}_i\) are the predictions from the model. We calculate the \(\hat{y}_i\) straight from the coeficients at some level of \(x_i\) that were interested in.

For example, lets say you wanted \(\hat{y}_i\) for length=0.545, diameter=0.4250, height=0.1400, whole=0.7995, and mature=1 (the abalone is mature, either male or female).

There are a few ways we can do this:

Straight from the output

y1 <- 2.5515 + 0.545*(-11.5266) + 0.4250*(18.3895) + 0.1400*(42.3253) + 0.7995*(-0.7085) + 1*(0.9101)
y1
## [1] 10.35424

Use the predict() function with the new data argument

#?predict.lm()

# new_x is just a data frame containing all the information on the points we want predictions for
# You have to include all variables that were in the model fit, and they must be in the same format
new_x <- data.frame(length=0.545, 
                    diameter=0.4250,
                    height=0.1400,
                    whole=0.7995,
                    mature=as.factor("M"))
y2 <- predict(object = model.fit, newdata=new_x)
y2
##        1 
## 10.35433

Looks like we have some rounding errors, but y1 and y2 are essentially the same value (y1 probably has the rounding error since we just copied the output from the summary).

Using linear algebra

# When using the linear algebra method make sure to include a leading '1' for the intercept coeficient
vec_x <- as.matrix(c(1, 0.545, 0.4250, 0.1400, 0.7995, 1))
b <- as.matrix(coef(model.fit),ncol=1)

y3 <- t(vec_x)%*%b
y3
##          [,1]
## [1,] 10.35433

y6 <- t(vec_x)%*%b

##          [,1]
## [1,] 9.444182

Simulations

The simulations are the predictions plus the stochastic (random) component.

We assumed \(\epsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2)\).

So, lets just add that random noise to all 6 of the predictions weve made so far.

y1.sim <- y1 + rnorm(n = 1, mean = 0, sd = sigma(model.fit))
y2.sim <- y2 + rnorm(n = 1, mean = 0, sd = sigma(model.fit))
y3.sim <- y3 + rnorm(n = 1, mean = 0, sd = sigma(model.fit))
y4.sim <- y4 + rnorm(n = 1, mean = 0, sd = sigma(model.fit))
y5.sim <- y5 + rnorm(n = 1, mean = 0, sd = sigma(model.fit))
y6.sim <- y6 + rnorm(n = 1, mean = 0, sd = sigma(model.fit))

y1.sim
## [1] 11.124
y2.sim
##        1 
## 8.983498
y3.sim
##          [,1]
## [1,] 10.62237
y4.sim
## [1] 9.237203
y5.sim
##        1 
## 7.212311
y6.sim
##         [,1]
## [1,] 12.2222

Thats it. Weve simulated 6 new data points from 2 \(\hat{y}_i\) values.

Predictions/simulations over a grid of possible values

Predictions

Lets say that you want to make a lot of new predictions. Youll need to have a new data frame or matrix representing the new predictor combinations for which you want predictions. Again, we can do this by hand, using predict(), or by using linear algebra.

First we need to set up the new data. Well do this by making a grid of possible new predictor levels. There are other ways to do this that maintian the predictor variable correlation structure (resampling and simulation should work), but this is fine for now.

# Create all the levels of each predictor that we're interested in

length <- seq(min(data2$length),max(data2$length),length.out = 5)
diameter <- seq(min(data2$diameter),max(data2$diameter),length.out = 5)
height <- seq(min(data2$height),max(data2$height),length.out = 5)
whole <- seq(min(data2$whole),max(data2$whole),length.out = 5)
mature <- c(0,1)

# Make all possible combinations 
grid <- expand.grid(length,diameter,height,whole,mature)

# Tidy-up the names (remember that the predict function needs the names to be right)
names(grid) <- c("length","diameter","height","whole","mature")

Create the predictions By hand

library(tidyverse)

grid_pred_1 <- grid%>%
  mutate(yhat=2.5515-11.5266*length+18.3895*diameter+42.3253*height-0.7085*whole+ 0.9101*mature)

Create the predictions using the predict function

grid2<- grid%>%
  mutate(mature=ifelse(mature==0,"I","M"))
grid_pred_2 <- predict(model.fit,newdata = grid2)

Create the predictions using matrix algebra

int <- matrix(1,nrow=nrow(grid),ncol=1)
grid3 <- cbind(int,as.matrix(grid))

b <- as.matrix(coef(model.fit),ncol=1)

grid_pred_3 <- grid3%*%b

Simulations

Just add the random component of the model to the prediction as before.

grid_sim_1 <- grid_pred_1%>%
  mutate(err=rnorm(n = nrow(grid_pred_1),mean = 0,sd = sigma(model.fit)))%>%
  mutate(sim=yhat+err)

Done!

We can make sure it worked by plotting our predicted values vs the simulated values (should be a 1 to 1 relationship with some noise). I made this graph using esquisser() and just copied the code over.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(grid_sim_1) +
 aes(x = yhat, y = sim) +
 geom_point(size = 1.44, colour = "#b4de2c") +
 labs(x = "Predicted values", y = "Simulated values", title = "Simulated vs predicted", subtitle = "A pretty graph", caption = "And a caption! Although the caption doesn't look great in this format.")

Logistic fits

Predict maturity

Fit a model

Here well try to fit a model to predict the probability of an abalone being mature or not based on information we fit find in the fossil record. Well use ring number and shell weight.

Remember how our predicted vs observed graph looked for model.fit? It looked like we may want to consider grouping abalones into old and young categories. Lets do that here, and also create an alternative mature column that takes on numeric values rather than factor levels (gam will need this).

data3 <- data2%>%
  mutate(ring_cat=as.factor(ifelse(rings>=10,"10+","young")))%>%
  mutate(mature_int=ifelse(mature=="I",0,1))
data3$ring_cat<- relevel(data3$ring_cat, ref="young")
data3$mature<- relevel(data3$mature, ref="I")

fit.log1 <- glm(mature ~ ring_cat*shell, data = data3, family = binomial())

Great!

Check linearity

Remember that we need to make sure that the relationship between the logodds and our continuous predictor variable is linear. Lets use gam to do that.

Im not going to cover the gam function in detail yet. Heres the code for now.

library(mgcv)
## Loading required package: nlme
## 
## Attaching package: 'nlme'

## 
##     collapse
## This is mgcv 1.8-28. For overview type 'help("mgcv-package")'.
gam1 <- gam(mature_int~s(shell),family="binomial",data=data3)

# plot(mature~shell, data=data3)
pp <- expand.grid(shell=seq(0,1,length=101),ring_cat=as.factor(c("young","10+")))
pp$y <- predict(gam1,newdata=pp)
# with(pp,lines(data3$shell,data3$mature))

plot(pp$shell,pp$y)

Looks like theres a slight bend. Maybe we should consider adding a quadratic term for shell.

fit.log2 <- glm(mature ~ ring_cat*shell + I(shell^2), data = data3, family = binomial())

AIC(fit.log1)
## [1] 3484.429
AIC(fit.log2)
## [1] 3465.826

Looks like the addition of the quadratic term helps.

Predictions and simulations from a logistic fit

Lets use the simpler model fit.log1 for this example. Note that were predicting the probability that an abalone is mature. Note also that ring_cat10+ is not the reference level.

Lets predict the probability that an abalone is mature given that it has 12 rings and a shell weight of 0.3.

Lets make a function that generates probabilities from log-odds. This is just algebra.

# This function that we save as "invlogit" will convert odds to probabilities
invlogit <- function(odds){
  exp(odds)/(1+exp(odds))
}

Straight from the output

ya1 <- -2.5286 + 1*(2.1715) + 0.3*(15.6604) + 1*0.3*(-7.0929)
ya1
## [1] 2.21315
invlogit(ya1)
## [1] 0.9014242

Use the predict() function with the new data argument

new_x <- data.frame(shell=0.3, 
                    ring_cat="10+")
ya2 <- predict(object = fit.log1, newdata=new_x)
ya2
##        1 
## 2.213113
invlogit(ya2)
##         1 
## 0.9014209

Using linear algebra

# When using the linear algebra method make sure to include a leading '1' for the intercept coeficient
vec_x <- as.matrix(c(1, 1, 0.3, 0.3*1))
b <- as.matrix(coef(fit.log1),ncol=1)

ya3 <- t(vec_x)%*%b
ya3
##          [,1]
## [1,] 2.213113
invlogit(ya3)
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.9014209

And what happens if the ring number is 5 instead? Notice that some of the terms just drop out due to the dummy variable coding.

Straight from the output

ya4 <- -2.5286 + 0*(2.1715) + 0.3*(15.6604) + 0*0.3*(-7.0929)
ya4
## [1] 2.16952
invlogit(ya4)
## [1] 0.8974788

Use the predict() function with the new data argument

new_x <- data.frame(shell=0.3, 
                    ring_cat="young")
ya5 <- predict(object = fit.log1, newdata=new_x)
ya5
##        1 
## 2.169483
invlogit(ya5)
##         1 
## 0.8974754

Using linear algebra

# When using the linear algebra method make sure to include a leading '1' for the intercept coeficient
vec_x <- as.matrix(c(1, 0, 0.3, 0.3*0))
b <- as.matrix(coef(fit.log1),ncol=1)

ya6 <- t(vec_x)%*%b
ya6
##          [,1]
## [1,] 2.169483
invlogit(ya6)
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.8974754

If we want to simulate 10 observations from one of these predicted values we just need to use the rbinom() function. (Theres a reason we set the family = binom). size is going to be equal to 1 since were simulating binary data (just 0s and 1s).

rbinom(n = 10, size = 1, prob = invlogit(ya6))
##  [1] 0 1 1 0 1 1 1 1 1 1

Thats it!

Predict Ring number

This section isnt testable, so my notes will be very sparse.

Instead of using a linear or poisson model to predict ring number we could try using a multinomial or ordinal model (essentially multiple logistic regressions).

I had some problems with high standard errors for the multinomial fit so I eliminated a predictor (whole, reduced multicolinearity) and binned the some of the outcome levels. It seemed to help.

newdat <- data.frame(
  curt_vol = data2$curt_vol,
  whole = data2$whole,
  mature = data2$mature)

newdata2 <- data2%>%
  mutate(rings=as.ordered(rings))

library(MASS)
library(nnet)
multi_1=multinom(rings~curt_vol + whole + mature , data = newdata2)

Creating logit/inverse logit functions

For interest.

# This function that we save as "logit" will convert probabilities to odds

logit <- function(probs) {
    log(probs/(1-probs))
}

# This function that we save as "invlogit" will convert odds to probabilities
invlogit <- function(odds){
  exp(odds)/(1+exp(odds))
}
